tic perception of language sounds. An account of the history of perceptual phonetics and the theoretical position of the subject as a specialist discipline is followed by an experimental study which derives psycho-physiological measures and acoustically evoked potentials and thus supports the assumption that both the general auditory processing mechanism and a special language processor are involved in the perception of sounds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 4aEvozierte Potentiale. 4aHören. 4aNeurolinguistik. 4aSprachpsychologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2005z9783110277111oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2005z9783110276886oZDB-23-DGA0 cprintz978311018279840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311092545640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110925456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110925456/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGAb2005  aZDB-23-DGGb2005  aZDB-23-DLSc2000d2014